15. perdiderit . . . adflixerit: the perfect subjunctive, though a primary tense, is often in consecutive clauses used (as equivalent to an aorist) in dependence on a historic principal verb. The perfect subjunctive thus used states an actual result rather than a natural consequence. quos . . . ab eis: quos refers to the whole citizen body, ab iis to a part only of that body, viz. the Marian faction.
